tion dedicated to humanitarian work and community building. A passionate Zionist, Szold was troubled by the Jewish–Arab conflict in Palestine, to which she sought a peaceful and equitable solution for all. Noted Israeli historian Dvora Hacohen captures the dramatic life of this remarkable woman. Long before anyone had heard of intersectionality, Szold maintained that her many political commitments were inseparable. She fought relentlessly for women’s place in Judaism and for health and educational networks in Mandate Palestine. As a global citizen, she championed American pacifism. Hacohen also offers a penetrating look into Szold’s personal world, revealing for the first time the psychogenic blindness that afflicted her as the result of a harrowing breakup with a famous Talmudic scholar. Based on letters and personal diaries, many previously unpublished, as well as thousands of archival documents scattered across three continents, To Repair a Broken World provides a wide-ranging portrait of a woman who devoted herself to helping the disadvantaged and building a future free of need.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aJewish womenvBiography. 0aZionistsvBiography. 0aZionistszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Women.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073911440uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067425918840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674259188423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674259188/original  a978-3-11-073911-4  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles